sections.body:
Your reference gain is a promise with conditions. When the side-drilled hole peaked at 80% FSH, that number bundled together the probe's efficiency, the couplant's transfer, the block's surface, and the block's attenuation. Carry the system to a part where **any of those transfer conditions differ** and the same flaw returns a different echo — usually smaller. Everything that governs how much energy crosses into the part, survives the round trip, and gets back out is a **transmission factor**:

- the **transducer** — its condition, wear, and identity;
- the **couplant** — type, film, temperature, chemistry;
- the **material** — surface, curvature, grain structure, temperature.

The danger is that it's invisible: the instrument still looks calibrated, the screen still draws crisp echoes, and the gain control still sits on the recorded number. But the *system* is no longer the system you standardized. This lesson covers each factor, the measured fix — **transfer correction** — and the rules for when nothing short of full re-standardization will do.

Re-standardization is triggered by **change, suspicion, and the clock**:

- any change of probe, wedge, cable, couplant, or instrument settings;
- a new examination surface, a different material, a significantly different temperature;
- suspected damage — the probe was dropped, the cable pinched, readings turned strange;
- the procedure's fixed intervals — and always a **closing check** at the end of the examination period, because that check validates everything since the last good one.

The closing check's verdict matters in two directions, and they are not symmetric. Recheck the reference reflector and find the response has **dropped** beyond the procedure's allowance: the system lost sensitivity at some unknown point, flaws may have slipped past — **everything examined since the last valid check is re-examined**. Find the response has **risen**: the system was over-sensitive, nothing was missed, but recorded indications were measured against the wrong yardstick — **re-evaluate the recorded indications** at the corrected level.

That asymmetry is the whole logic of calibration discipline. Checks cost minutes; a failed closing check can cost a day of rework. So verify at every natural pause — probe changes, breaks, suspicious signals — not just when the procedure forces you. The calibration is never yours to assume. It is yours to prove, repeatedly, until the report is signed.
